comments.undefined: The STORM (STOrytelling and Metaphors) ontology examines metaphors and their connections to storytelling theories by influential scholars. More specifically, the ontology focuses on metaphors found in Shakespearean works and the ways in which they reflect the universality of narrative structure, as anticipated in theories of narratology. With this project we attempt to demonstrate that metaphors do not only shed light on universal narrative elements, but that they may also provide insight into the main ideas of a story.

Greimas' work on semiotics and narratology make him one of the most important scholars in the field, with theories on the structure of a story and character archetypes. His work allowed us to search for and draw connections between structure and metaphors, with the latter reflecting important events of each narrative stage, bringing forth the motivations and aims of the main characters and adding to the semantic redundancy of the dominant themes of the story.

A collection of theories on narration and semiotics that allow a complete overview of the important elements in the narrative structure of a story: the flow of events, the characters, the setting. The theories were chosen for their links to narratology and, therefore, their potential to bring forth the universality of narrative structure as reflected in metaphors, which is what we aspire to demonstrate with this ontology.

This class includes important theories on the universal division of the narrative structure. We employed Hegel's stages, Greimas' narrative program and Yorke's midpoint to divide the plays and define the location of the metaphors. It is worth mentioning here that what is of importance is not the physical location of the metaphors in the story (e.g. the scene, the act etc), but their narrative location, i.e. the specific moment in the flow of events in which they were articulated.
